1. System Layers

A. Appraisal Layer

Purpose:
Estimate contribution value at intake.

Inputs:
	•	item identity
	•	condition
	•	completeness
	•	rarity
	•	authenticity confidence
	•	current market comps
	•	liquidity / demand
	•	replacement difficulty
	•	storage and handling cost

Output:
A scored valuation object.

Example:

{
  "item_id": "pkm_001",
  "appraised_value": 185.0,
  "condition_score": 0.88,
  "authenticity_confidence": 0.97,
  "liquidity_score": 0.74,
  "valuation_confidence": 0.91
}

Rule

AI handles the bulk.
Humans handle:
	•	disputes
	•	edge cases
	•	high-value items
	•	fraud review

⸻

B. Custodial Library Layer

Purpose:
Hold real inventory in trusted custody.

Functions:
	•	intake
	•	cataloging
	•	condition scan
	•	storage
	•	retrieval
	•	shipping / local pickup
	•	return processing

This is what separates the system from loose peer-to-peer chaos.

The value is not just the credit engine.
It is the combination of:

appraisal + storage + trust + retrieval

⸻

C. Credit Ledger Layer

Purpose:
Translate contributed value into usable access.

Credits are:
	•	issued when assets are accepted
	•	backed by real appraised inventory
	•	spent, locked, restored, or penalized according to policy

Credit types:
	•	deposit credit: earned from contribution
	•	reserved credit: temporarily locked during checkout
	•	reputation-adjusted credit: modified by trust score and history

Core rule

Credits must remain visibly backed by inventory and rules.

No fake points.
No hidden inflation.

⸻

D. Trust and Integrity Layer

Purpose:
Protect the pool from fraud, damage, and distortion.

Mechanisms:
	•	chain of custody
	•	image and scan records
	•	before/after condition comparison
	•	anomaly detection
	•	reputation system
	•	audit sampling
	•	insurance / risk pool
	•	dispute workflow

This is where the system becomes serious.

Without this layer, it collapses into:
	•	fake submissions
	•	condition disputes
	•	trust erosion

⸻

E. Matching and Access Layer

Purpose:
Let users draw value back out.

Modes:
	•	borrow
	•	exchange
	•	redeem
	•	reserve
	•	permanent transfer
	•	temporary checkout

Matching factors:
	•	credit balance
	•	inventory availability
	•	demand queue
	•	reputation
	•	geographic logistics
	•	circulation policy

